Question 2

Use different visualization tools to summarize the data sets in this question.

  1. Using the PlantGrowth data set, visualize and compare the weight of the plant in the three separated group. Give labels to the title, x-axis, and y-axis on the graph. Write a paragraph to summarize your findings.
# Load the data set
data("PlantGrowth")

# Head of the data set
head(PlantGrowth)
# Enter your code here!
groups <- c("weight 1", "weight 2", "weight 3")
weightRanges <- c(4, 5, 6, 7)
weightCut <- cut(PlantGrowth$weight, breaks = weightRanges, labels = groups)
weightCut
##  [1] weight 1 weight 2 weight 2 weight 3 weight 1 weight 1 weight 2 weight 1
##  [9] weight 2 weight 2 weight 1 weight 1 weight 1 <NA>     weight 2 <NA>    
## [17] weight 3 weight 1 weight 1 weight 1 weight 3 weight 2 weight 2 weight 2
## [25] weight 2 weight 2 weight 1 weight 3 weight 2 weight 2
## Levels: weight 1 weight 2 weight 3
barplot(PlantGrowth$weight, names.arg = weightCut, ylab = "weight", xlab = "group", main = "plant weight by groups")

Result:

=> Report a paragraph to summarize your findings from the plot! We can note from the bar graph that typical ranges for weight lay between 4 and 6. Within each class subgroup we can also see outliers. Weight three was the group that presented with the lowest ranges and a standard outlier. As was present in other sets.

  1. Using the USArrests data set, create a pairs plot to display the correlations between the variables in the data set. Plot the scatter plot with Murder and Assault. Give labels to the title, x-axis, and y-axis on the graph. Write a paragraph to summarize your results from both plots.
# Load the data set
data("USArrests")

# Head of the data set
head(USArrests)
colors <- c("pink", "blue")

# Enter your code here!
plot(USArrests$Murder, USArrests$Assault, col = colors, main = "Murder vs. Assault", xlab = "Murder", ylab= "Assault")

Result:

=> Report a paragraph to summarize your findings from the plot!

We can see that Assault and are STRONGLY linearlly correlated. As assaults become more frequent, so do murders. Murders typically do not occur at high rates without assault. They are highest in frequency when both cases are reported together.
